history.content: If you are currently applying into the major, then you will move up both the discussion and lecture waitlist ahead of non-CS majors when your application is processed.  Also, discussion is more important, so prioritize finding a discussion with a high number of open seats.

children.subject:
If you are the first person on the course waitlist who can get into both lecture + discussion, then you get in.

So, if you switch to a different open discussion, and there are also open seats in the lecture (which should be the case during the adjustment period as you specified), then you get in, yes.

If there aren't open seats in lecture, then you won't be able to get in. This is as true for 61C as it is for 188, but generally, if there are open seats in section, then there'll be open seats in lecture (assuming there aren't any seat restrictions).

I am position 52 on the waitlist right now (will petition to declare this Spring), and the discussion I signed up for was open when I signed up. But now it is full and has ~30 people on the waitlist. I don't know my rank for the discussion waitlist is. 

The waitlist for 188 has over 300 people on it. If I were to switch to one of the open discussions what would happen? I assume that the way it works is I lose my position on the course waitlist and move to the back if I try to switch to another discussion. If I did change to one of the open discussions would I be enrolled in the class, essentially bypassing all the 300+ people on the waitlist? IOW, does the course waitlist matter at all if you enroll into an open discussion section? Assume we're talking about doing this during adjustment period, when non-declared students can move off the waitlist. 

When we were enrolling for CS61C they told us if we could sign up for a discussion we would be in the class. Is that how it will work with 188 too?
